    <thetext>//----
@org.eclipse.jdt.annotation.NonNullByDefault
public class Test&lt;E&gt; {
	void test() throws E {}
}
//----

Error:

	void test() throws E {}
                           ^
Nullness annotations are not applicable at this location</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2428458</commentid>
    <comment_count>1</comment_count>
    <who name="Stephan Herrmann">stephan.herrmann</who>
    <bug_when>2014-07-16 13:25:14 -0400</bug_when>
    <thetext>Example should be:

//----
@org.eclipse.jdt.annotation.NonNullByDefault
public class Test&lt;E extends Exception&gt; {
	void test() throws E {}
}
//----

Now the default clearly applies to the explicit upper bound of E.

Root cause of the bug: this analysis for illegal location of null type annotation uses information from the binding, where it should use information from the AST.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
